<br />
Which was my point. A trailer very deliberately accentuates some things and ignores others, because there is limited time to gain a viewer's interest. You aren't usually going to get evidence of &quot;character development&quot; in 1:30. (although it is possible) I used Gravity as an example because it, even more than Ender's Game, is not an action movie. And despite this, the trailer was still framed to seem exciting. Therefore you cannot assume that Ender's Game is just a pew pew space battle movie because the trailer didn't feature 30 seconds of Valentine and Peter talking about politics on the internet (not that I think that will be in the movie, mind you).<br />
<br />
Everyone that has read the books already knows the movie exists, they don't need a trailer to convince you to watch it. They need a trailer to convince the people who did not read the book to watch it.
